select null, 'history-mughals-ch01', $chapter${"id":"history-mughals-ch01","subject":"History","chapterNumber":1,"title":"The Advent of the Mughals","source":"Sarrthi IAS · GS Foundation · UPSC Prelims 2028 · History","description":"Babur's takeover from the Lodis, Humayun and Sher Shah Suri, the re-establishment of the Mughal kingdom at Panipat 1556, Akbar's Mansabdari system, Mughal land revenue from Zabti to Ijaradari, and Akbar's religious vision.","tags":["medieval-india","mughals","akbar","land-revenue"],"prelims":[{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p1","origin":"FYQ_Pre_1","statement":"Consider the following statements about Babur (r. 1526–30):\n1. He was a descendant of Timur (Tamerlane), whose 1398 invasion of Delhi had already weakened the Delhi Sultanate.\n2. He came to power in Fergana but lost it by 1512, though he did hold Kabul.\n3. He attacked the Delhi Sultanate from 1519 with artillery support from the Ottoman Empire.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"Statement 1 ✓ — 'Mughal Take Over from Lodis': Babur was a descendant of Timur (Tamerlane), whose 1398 invasion of Delhi had already weakened the Delhi Sultanate.\nStatement 2 ✓ — 'Mughal Take Over from Lodis': Babur came to power young but could not hold Fergana; by 1512 his Central Asian ambitions had collapsed; he did hold Kabul (captured 1504).\nStatement 3 ✓ — 'Mughal Take Over from Lodis': With artillery support from the Ottoman Empire (expert gunners), Babur began attacking the Delhi Sultanate from 1519.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["babur","mughal-takeover"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p2","origin":"FYQ_Pre_2","statement":"Which one of the following best explains why three of the most consequential battles in Indian history (1526, 1556, 1761) were fought at Panipat?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Panipat was the political capital of the Lodi dynasty."},{"id":"b","text":"Panipat sat in a narrow corridor between the Thar Desert and the Himalayan foothills, with the Yamuna acting as a defensive choke-point."},{"id":"c","text":"Panipat was the only flat plain in north India suitable for cannon warfare."},{"id":"d","text":"Panipat was midway between Delhi and Lahore, making it logistically convenient."}],"answer":"b","explanation":"✓ — 'Mughal Take Over from Lodis': Three geographical factors converged at Panipat — proximity to the Khyber Pass (primary invasion route), narrow corridor between Thar Desert (south) and Himalayan foothills (north), and the Yamuna to the east as a defensive choke-point.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["panipat","geography"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p3","origin":"FYQ_Pre_3","statement":"Match the following Sher Shah Suri (r. 1540–45) reforms with their content:\n1. Revenue — A. Silver coin of standardised weight and purity\n2. Currency — B. Peshawar to Sonargaon road\n3. Infrastructure — C. Patta + Qabuliyat two-document system","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1-A, 2-B, 3-C"},{"id":"b","text":"1-C, 2-A, 3-B"},{"id":"c","text":"1-B, 2-C, 3-A"},{"id":"d","text":"1-C, 2-B, 3-A"}],"answer":"b","explanation":"'Humayun30-40 & Sher Shah Suri40-45 (1540-45)':\nReform 1 (Revenue) — Patta + Qabuliyat two-document system ('Revenue').\nReform 2 (Currency) — Silver Rupiya of standardised weight and purity ('Currency').\nReform 3 (Infrastructure) — Grand Trunk Road from Peshawar to Sonargaon ('Infrastructure').","difficulty":"medium","tags":["sher-shah-suri","reforms"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p4","origin":"FYQ_Pre_4","statement":"Consider the following statements regarding Humayun's (r. 1530–40) Safavid alliance:\n1. He had to adopt Shia practices and outward observances.\n2. He had to cede control of Kandahar to Iran.\n3. Persian language and art became deeply embedded in Mughal court culture.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"'Humayun30-40 & Sher Shah Suri40-45 (1540-45)':\nStatement 1 ✓ — Humayun had to adopt Shia practices and outward observances.\nStatement 2 ✓ — Humayun had to cede control of Kandahar to Iran.\nStatement 3 ✓ — Persian language and art became deeply embedded in Mughal court culture; a distinct Irani group of Mansabdars later emerged within the Mughal administration.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["humayun","safavid-alliance"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p5","origin":"FYQ_Pre_5","statement":"With reference to the Second Battle of Panipat (1556), consider the following statements:\n1. On one side stood Hemchandra Vikramaditya (Hemu) controlling Delhi.\n2. The Mughal army was led by Bairam Khan, guardian to the thirteen-year-old Akbar.\n3. Hemu had earlier declared himself Samrat after seizing Delhi in 1556.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"'Humayun30-40 & Sher Shah Suri40-45 (1540-45)' and 'How was the Mughal Kingdom re-established (Panipat 1556)?':\nStatement 1 ✓ — 'How was the Mughal Kingdom re-established (Panipat 1556)?': Hemu controlled Delhi at the time of the Second Battle of Panipat (1556).\nStatement 2 ✓ — 'How was the Mughal Kingdom re-established (Panipat 1556)?': The Mughal army under Bairam Khan, general and guardian to the thirteen-year-old Akbar.\nStatement 3 ✓ — 'Humayun30-40 & Sher Shah Suri40-45 (1540-45)': Hemu seized Delhi after Humayun's death in January 1556 and declared himself Samrat.","difficulty":"easy","tags":["panipat-1556","hemu","bairam-khan"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p6","origin":"FYQ_Pre_6","statement":"In the Mansabdari System under Akbar (r. 1556–1605), what did the term Sawar rank denote?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Personal rank governing seniority and status"},{"id":"b","text":"The number of horsemen the Mansabdar must maintain and provide to the King"},{"id":"c","text":"The amount of land revenue the Mansabdar collected annually"},{"id":"d","text":"The size of the Mansabdar's hereditary jagir"}],"answer":"b","explanation":"✓ — 'How was rank determined? Zat + Sawar': Each Mansabdar carried two ranks — Zat (personal rank, governing seniority and status) and Sawar (the number of horsemen he must maintain and provide to the King). Net rank = Zat + Sawar.","difficulty":"easy","tags":["mansabdari","zat-sawar"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p7","origin":"FYQ_Pre_7","statement":"Which one of the following statements about a Watan Jagir is correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It was hereditary and permanent, given primarily to Rajput chieftains and autonomous rulers."},{"id":"b","text":"It was rotated among Mansabdars at the King's discretion."},{"id":"c","text":"Its accumulated wealth was confiscated on the death of the holder."},{"id":"d","text":"It was identical to a Tankha Jagir except in name."}],"answer":"a","explanation":"✓ — 'What was a Watan Jagir? Watan means hereditary and permanent': Watan means hereditary and permanent. Unlike Tankha Jagirs, a Watan Jagir could be passed down and was not subject to rotation or confiscation. Watan Jagirs were given primarily to Rajput chieftains and autonomous rulers who had submitted to the Emperor.\n(b) ✗ — That's the Tankha Jagir rule.\n(c) ✗ — That's also the Tankha Jagir rule (confiscation on death).\n(d) ✗ — Watan Jagir was hereditary; Tankha Jagir was rotational + confiscatable.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["watan-jagir","mansabdari"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p8","origin":"FYQ_Pre_8","statement":"With reference to the Mughal land categories, consider the following pairs:\n1. Jagir land — Revenue went to Mansabdars\n2. Khalisa land — Royal land; revenue went to the King\n3. Inam land — Gifted land; revenue went to a chosen beneficiary\nWhich of the pairs given above are correctly matched?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"'How were Mansabdars paid? Jagir, Khalisa, Inam':\nPair 1 ✓ — Jagir land: revenue to Mansabdars.\nPair 2 ✓ — Khalisa land: royal land; revenue went directly to the King and paid Naqdi Mansabdars plus other State expenses.\nPair 3 ✓ — Inam land: gifted land; revenue went to a chosen beneficiary (e.g. a man of exceptional talent) to sustain himself.","difficulty":"easy","tags":["land-categories","jagir","khalisa","inam"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p9","origin":"FYQ_Pre_9","statement":"Match the Mughal revenue hierarchy roles to their administrative levels:\n1. Patwari — A. Pargana\n2. Qanungo — B. Sarkar (district)\n3. Amalguzar — C. Village","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1-A, 2-B, 3-C"},{"id":"b","text":"1-C, 2-A, 3-B"},{"id":"c","text":"1-B, 2-C, 3-A"},{"id":"d","text":"1-A, 2-C, 3-B"}],"answer":"b","explanation":"'Who collected revenue':\nPatwari — Village level (maintained ledgers of individual peasant holdings and crops).\nQanungo — Pargana level (consolidated Patwari data; hereditary custodian of historical tax rates).\nAmalguzar — Sarkar (district) level (Amil at pargana level reported to Amalguzar at sarkar level).","difficulty":"medium","tags":["revenue-hierarchy","patwari","qanungo","amalguzar"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p10","origin":"FYQ_Pre_10","statement":"With reference to ryot categories under Mughal Land Revenue, consider the following statements:\n1. Khudkashts cultivated the same land year after year and acquired customary occupancy rights.\n2. Pahikashts cultivated different lands across different seasons and had no occupancy rights.\n3. Pahikashts were sometimes called Vagrant or Banjara peasants.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"'Who were the ryots':\nStatement 1 ✓ — Khudkashts cultivated the same land year after year and acquired customary occupancy rights, documented in a Patta.\nStatement 2 ✓ — Pahikashts cultivated different lands across different seasons, often as share-croppers, with no occupancy rights and no legal protections.\nStatement 3 ✓ — Pahikashts were sometimes called Vagrant or Banjara peasants because of this rootlessness.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["ryots","khudkasht","pahikasht"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p11","origin":"FYQ_Pre_11","statement":"Under Akbar's Zabti system, the Zamindar's legally fixed commission for collecting LR was approximately:","options":[{"id":"a","text":"5% (called Peshkash)"},{"id":"b","text":"10% (called Nankar or Malikana)"},{"id":"c","text":"15% (called Abwabs)"},{"id":"d","text":"20% (called Milkiyat)"}],"answer":"b","explanation":"✓ — 'Who collected revenue': Under Akbar's Zabti system, the Zamindar's legally fixed commission was around 10%, called Nankar or Malikana.\n(a) ✗ — Peshkash was the 10% tribute the Watan Jagir holder paid the King, not the Zamindar's commission.\n(c) ✗ — Abwabs were customary additional tributes, not the commission.\n(d) ✗ — Milkiyat was the Zamindar's own personal lands.","difficulty":"hard","tags":["zabti","zamindar","nankar-malikana"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p12","origin":"FYQ_Pre_12","statement":"Which one of the following best describes the Ijaradari System?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Direct state collection of revenue through scientifically measured demand under Akbar's centralised administration."},{"id":"b","text":"Auctioning the right to collect taxes to a private bidder (an Ijaradar or Revenue Farmer) for a 3- to 5-year contract."},{"id":"c","text":"Hereditary Zamindari grants given to Rajput chieftains in exchange for military service."},{"id":"d","text":"Cash payments to Mansabdars in lieu of Jagir grants."}],"answer":"b","explanation":"'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system': The right to collect all revenues from an area — land, traders, shopkeepers — was auctioned to the highest bidder, called an Ijaradar or Revenue Farmer; contracts were typically 3 to 5 years.\n(a) ✗ — That describes the Zabti system, not Ijaradari.\n(c) ✗ — describes Watan Jagir grants.\n(d) ✗ — describes Naqdi Mansabdar payment.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["ijaradari","revenue-farming"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p13","origin":"FYQ_Pre_13","statement":"Arrange the following Mughal-era Ijaradari milestones in correct chronological order:\n1. Akbar abolished revenue farming and replaced it with the Zabti system.\n2. Jahandar Shah (r. 1712–13) institutionalised Ijaradari in Punjab and Bengal.\n3. Farukhsiyar (r. 1713–19) extended Ijaradari into royal Khalisa lands.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 — 2 — 3"},{"id":"b","text":"2 — 1 — 3"},{"id":"c","text":"1 — 3 — 2"},{"id":"d","text":"3 — 2 — 1"}],"answer":"a","explanation":"'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system':\n1. Akbar (1556–1605) practically abolished Ijaradari and replaced it with the Zabti system.\n2. Jahandar Shah (1712–13) institutionalised Ijaradari in the richest provinces — Punjab and Bengal.\n3. Farukhsiyar (1713–19) extended Ijaradari fatally into royal Khalisa lands.","difficulty":"easy","tags":["ijaradari","chronology"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p14","origin":"FYQ_Pre_14","statement":"With reference to Akbar's religious vision, consider the following statements:\n1. Ibadat Khana (1575) was established at Fatehpur Sikri for inter-faith debates.\n2. The Mahzar (1579) made the Emperor, not the clergy, the final authority on religious disputes.\n3. The Din-i-Ilahi (1582) drew on Islam, Hinduism, Zoroastrianism, and Christianity but attracted very few formal followers.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?':\nStatement 1 ✓ — 'Ibadat Khana (1575)': Ibadat Khana 1575, House of Worship at Fatehpur Sikri.\nStatement 2 ✓ — 'Mahzar': Mahzar 1579, Emperor (not the clergy) became final word on matters of faith.\nStatement 3 ✓ — 'Din-i-Ilahi (1582)': Din-i-Ilahi 1582, syncretic order borrowing from Islam, Hinduism, Zoroastrianism, & Christianity; very few formal followers.","difficulty":"easy","tags":["akbar","religious-vision","din-i-ilahi"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p15","origin":"FYQ_Pre_15","statement":"Which one of the following statements about the introduction of Jizya in India is correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Muhammad bin Qasim first imposed Jizya in Sindh during the 8th-century Arab conquest."},{"id":"b","text":"Qutb-ud-din Aibak first introduced Jizya in India in the early 13th century."},{"id":"c","text":"Akbar was the first ruler to abolish Jizya across the Mughal Empire."},{"id":"d","text":"Aurangzeb was the first ruler to impose Jizya across the Indian subcontinent."}],"answer":"a","explanation":"'Who actually introduced Jizya in India?': Muhammad bin Qasim first imposed Jizya in Sindh during the Arab conquest of the 8th century.\n(b) ✗ — Qutb-ud-din Aibak and his successors institutionalised Jizya as a formal instrument across the Delhi Sultanate from the early 13th century, but did not first introduce it.\n(c) ✗ — Akbar abolished Jizya, but he was not the first ruler to do so (intermediate rulers had varied policies).\n(d) ✗ — Aurangzeb reimposed Jizya, but it had existed in India for centuries before him.","difficulty":"hard","tags":["jizya","taxation"]}],"mains":[{"id":"hist-mg-c1-m1","origin":"PYQ_M.1","question":"\"Examine the main aspects of Akbar's religious syncretism.\"","keyPoints":["Ibadat Khana (1575) — House of Worship at Fatehpur Sikri; multi-faith debates; exposed Akbar to diversity of religious thought and to bitter Ulama rivalries (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?').","Mahzar (1579) — Infallibility Decree — gave Akbar authority to adjudicate religious disputes; effectively made the Emperor, not the clergy, the final word on matters of faith (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?').","Din-i-Ilahi (1582) — syncretic spiritual order borrowing from Islam, Hinduism, Zoroastrianism, & Christianity; very few formal followers; significance lay in the principle expressed (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?').","Sulh-i-Kul — universal peace — State must treat all religions with equal respect; no single faith should dominate policy. Became the ideological foundation of Mughal governance under Akbar and continued to influence Mughal politics long after his death (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?')."],"modelAnswer":"Closing line: the four-part sequence (Ibadat Khana → Mahzar → Din-i-Ilahi → Sulh-i-Kul) shows Akbar moving deliberately from open inter-faith debate, to State authority over religion, to a syncretic spiritual formulation, to a governing principle that outlasted his reign.","explanation":"PYQ_M.1 — Mains 2025 — Mughal Religious Vision (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?'). No other PYQs from the verified 1996–2025 bank anchor solely to Ch 1.","wordLimit":150,"marks":10,"difficulty":"medium","tags":["akbar","religious-syncretism","sulh-i-kul"],"year":2025},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-m2","origin":"FYQ_M.1","question":"Examine the institutional foundations laid by Babur and Akbar for the Mughal Empire's longevity.","keyPoints":["Babur's establishment of the dynasty (1526) — Panipat I victory, geographic anchor in the Delhi heartland, integration of Central Asian (Timurid) and Indian governance traditions (see 'Mughal Take Over from Lodis').","Akbar's land revenue revolution — the Zabti system based on scientifically measured demand + a salaried bureaucracy under the Mansabdari system replaced the older revenue-farming model (see 'How did Akbar56-05 build the Mughal State — the Mansabdari System' and 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Akbar's religious-administrative synthesis — Sulh-i-Kul as State doctrine; Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, and Din-i-Ilahi as institutional expressions; Watan Jagirs for Rajput integration (see 'How did Akbar56-05 build the Mughal State — the Mansabdari System' and 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?').","Persianate court culture under Humayun's Safavid alliance — Persian language, art, and administrative grammar became the imperial standard (see 'Humayun30-40 & Sher Shah Suri40-45 (1540-45)').","Conclusion: the founding generations built four institutional pillars — political (dynasty), economic (Zabti), military-administrative (Mansabdari), and ideological (Sulh-i-Kul) — that together explain why the Mughal Empire could absorb pressures for nearly two centuries (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?')."],"modelAnswer":"Conclusion: the founding generations built four institutional pillars — political (dynasty), economic (Zabti), military-administrative (Mansabdari), and ideological (Sulh-i-Kul) — that together explain why the Mughal Empire could absorb pressures for nearly two centuries.","explanation":"Demand: Identify the founding-era institutions and weigh how each contributed to the Mughal Empire's later longevity.","wordLimit":250,"marks":15,"difficulty":"medium","tags":["babur","akbar","institutions","mansabdari","zabti"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-m3","origin":"FYQ_M.2","question":"Discuss the evolution of the Mughal land revenue system from Akbar's Zabti to the late-Mughal Ijaradari, and its consequences for the State and the peasantry.","keyPoints":["Akbar's Zabti (1556-1605) — scientifically measured demand based on area + average yield + standard prices, with the Patwari-Qanungo-Amalguzar hierarchy reporting on actual cultivation. State capacity high; peasant burden predictable (see 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Continuation under Akbar's successors — Jahangir, Shah Jahan, and early Aurangzeb retained the framework, with limited shifts to Ijaradari at the margins (see 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Jahandar Shah (1712-13) — first institutionalisation of Ijaradari in the richest provinces (Punjab + Bengal); private bidders bought 3-5 year revenue rights at auction (see 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Farukhsiyar (1713-19) — fatal extension of Ijaradari into royal Khalisa lands; the State's own income now came through middlemen with extractive incentives (see 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Consequence for the State — short-term cash inflow but loss of administrative knowledge about real revenue capacity; the State's grip on revenue weakened over decades.","Consequence for the peasantry — Ijaradars had 3-5 year horizons, no incentive for long-term investment; over-extraction, peasant flight, and the rise of revenue arrears characterise the later-Mughal countryside (see 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Conclusion: the Zabti-to-Ijaradari trajectory mirrors the wider Mughal decline — institutional rigour gave way to short-term cash, with State capacity and peasant welfare both eroding in parallel."],"modelAnswer":"Conclusion: the Zabti-to-Ijaradari trajectory mirrors the wider Mughal decline — institutional rigour gave way to short-term cash, with State capacity and peasant welfare both eroding in parallel.","explanation":"Demand: Trace the change from Akbar's scientifically measured Zabti to the auction-based Ijaradari, and assess what each meant for State capacity and peasant welfare.","wordLimit":250,"marks":15,"difficulty":"medium","tags":["zabti","ijaradari","land-revenue","mughal-decline"]}]}$chapter$::jsonb,
       $chapter${"id":"history-mughals-ch01","subject":"History","chapterNumber":1,"title":"The Advent of the Mughals","source":"Sarrthi IAS · GS Foundation · UPSC Prelims 2028 · History","description":"Babur's takeover from the Lodis, Humayun and Sher Shah Suri, the re-establishment of the Mughal kingdom at Panipat 1556, Akbar's Mansabdari system, Mughal land revenue from Zabti to Ijaradari, and Akbar's religious vision.","tags":["medieval-india","mughals","akbar","land-revenue"],"prelims":[{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p1","origin":"FYQ_Pre_1","statement":"Consider the following statements about Babur (r. 1526–30):\n1. He was a descendant of Timur (Tamerlane), whose 1398 invasion of Delhi had already weakened the Delhi Sultanate.\n2. He came to power in Fergana but lost it by 1512, though he did hold Kabul.\n3. He attacked the Delhi Sultanate from 1519 with artillery support from the Ottoman Empire.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"Statement 1 ✓ — 'Mughal Take Over from Lodis': Babur was a descendant of Timur (Tamerlane), whose 1398 invasion of Delhi had already weakened the Delhi Sultanate.\nStatement 2 ✓ — 'Mughal Take Over from Lodis': Babur came to power young but could not hold Fergana; by 1512 his Central Asian ambitions had collapsed; he did hold Kabul (captured 1504).\nStatement 3 ✓ — 'Mughal Take Over from Lodis': With artillery support from the Ottoman Empire (expert gunners), Babur began attacking the Delhi Sultanate from 1519.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["babur","mughal-takeover"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p2","origin":"FYQ_Pre_2","statement":"Which one of the following best explains why three of the most consequential battles in Indian history (1526, 1556, 1761) were fought at Panipat?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Panipat was the political capital of the Lodi dynasty."},{"id":"b","text":"Panipat sat in a narrow corridor between the Thar Desert and the Himalayan foothills, with the Yamuna acting as a defensive choke-point."},{"id":"c","text":"Panipat was the only flat plain in north India suitable for cannon warfare."},{"id":"d","text":"Panipat was midway between Delhi and Lahore, making it logistically convenient."}],"answer":"b","explanation":"✓ — 'Mughal Take Over from Lodis': Three geographical factors converged at Panipat — proximity to the Khyber Pass (primary invasion route), narrow corridor between Thar Desert (south) and Himalayan foothills (north), and the Yamuna to the east as a defensive choke-point.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["panipat","geography"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p3","origin":"FYQ_Pre_3","statement":"Match the following Sher Shah Suri (r. 1540–45) reforms with their content:\n1. Revenue — A. Silver coin of standardised weight and purity\n2. Currency — B. Peshawar to Sonargaon road\n3. Infrastructure — C. Patta + Qabuliyat two-document system","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1-A, 2-B, 3-C"},{"id":"b","text":"1-C, 2-A, 3-B"},{"id":"c","text":"1-B, 2-C, 3-A"},{"id":"d","text":"1-C, 2-B, 3-A"}],"answer":"b","explanation":"'Humayun30-40 & Sher Shah Suri40-45 (1540-45)':\nReform 1 (Revenue) — Patta + Qabuliyat two-document system ('Revenue').\nReform 2 (Currency) — Silver Rupiya of standardised weight and purity ('Currency').\nReform 3 (Infrastructure) — Grand Trunk Road from Peshawar to Sonargaon ('Infrastructure').","difficulty":"medium","tags":["sher-shah-suri","reforms"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p4","origin":"FYQ_Pre_4","statement":"Consider the following statements regarding Humayun's (r. 1530–40) Safavid alliance:\n1. He had to adopt Shia practices and outward observances.\n2. He had to cede control of Kandahar to Iran.\n3. Persian language and art became deeply embedded in Mughal court culture.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"'Humayun30-40 & Sher Shah Suri40-45 (1540-45)':\nStatement 1 ✓ — Humayun had to adopt Shia practices and outward observances.\nStatement 2 ✓ — Humayun had to cede control of Kandahar to Iran.\nStatement 3 ✓ — Persian language and art became deeply embedded in Mughal court culture; a distinct Irani group of Mansabdars later emerged within the Mughal administration.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["humayun","safavid-alliance"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p5","origin":"FYQ_Pre_5","statement":"With reference to the Second Battle of Panipat (1556), consider the following statements:\n1. On one side stood Hemchandra Vikramaditya (Hemu) controlling Delhi.\n2. The Mughal army was led by Bairam Khan, guardian to the thirteen-year-old Akbar.\n3. Hemu had earlier declared himself Samrat after seizing Delhi in 1556.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"'Humayun30-40 & Sher Shah Suri40-45 (1540-45)' and 'How was the Mughal Kingdom re-established (Panipat 1556)?':\nStatement 1 ✓ — 'How was the Mughal Kingdom re-established (Panipat 1556)?': Hemu controlled Delhi at the time of the Second Battle of Panipat (1556).\nStatement 2 ✓ — 'How was the Mughal Kingdom re-established (Panipat 1556)?': The Mughal army under Bairam Khan, general and guardian to the thirteen-year-old Akbar.\nStatement 3 ✓ — 'Humayun30-40 & Sher Shah Suri40-45 (1540-45)': Hemu seized Delhi after Humayun's death in January 1556 and declared himself Samrat.","difficulty":"easy","tags":["panipat-1556","hemu","bairam-khan"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p6","origin":"FYQ_Pre_6","statement":"In the Mansabdari System under Akbar (r. 1556–1605), what did the term Sawar rank denote?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Personal rank governing seniority and status"},{"id":"b","text":"The number of horsemen the Mansabdar must maintain and provide to the King"},{"id":"c","text":"The amount of land revenue the Mansabdar collected annually"},{"id":"d","text":"The size of the Mansabdar's hereditary jagir"}],"answer":"b","explanation":"✓ — 'How was rank determined? Zat + Sawar': Each Mansabdar carried two ranks — Zat (personal rank, governing seniority and status) and Sawar (the number of horsemen he must maintain and provide to the King). Net rank = Zat + Sawar.","difficulty":"easy","tags":["mansabdari","zat-sawar"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p7","origin":"FYQ_Pre_7","statement":"Which one of the following statements about a Watan Jagir is correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It was hereditary and permanent, given primarily to Rajput chieftains and autonomous rulers."},{"id":"b","text":"It was rotated among Mansabdars at the King's discretion."},{"id":"c","text":"Its accumulated wealth was confiscated on the death of the holder."},{"id":"d","text":"It was identical to a Tankha Jagir except in name."}],"answer":"a","explanation":"✓ — 'What was a Watan Jagir? Watan means hereditary and permanent': Watan means hereditary and permanent. Unlike Tankha Jagirs, a Watan Jagir could be passed down and was not subject to rotation or confiscation. Watan Jagirs were given primarily to Rajput chieftains and autonomous rulers who had submitted to the Emperor.\n(b) ✗ — That's the Tankha Jagir rule.\n(c) ✗ — That's also the Tankha Jagir rule (confiscation on death).\n(d) ✗ — Watan Jagir was hereditary; Tankha Jagir was rotational + confiscatable.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["watan-jagir","mansabdari"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p8","origin":"FYQ_Pre_8","statement":"With reference to the Mughal land categories, consider the following pairs:\n1. Jagir land — Revenue went to Mansabdars\n2. Khalisa land — Royal land; revenue went to the King\n3. Inam land — Gifted land; revenue went to a chosen beneficiary\nWhich of the pairs given above are correctly matched?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"'How were Mansabdars paid? Jagir, Khalisa, Inam':\nPair 1 ✓ — Jagir land: revenue to Mansabdars.\nPair 2 ✓ — Khalisa land: royal land; revenue went directly to the King and paid Naqdi Mansabdars plus other State expenses.\nPair 3 ✓ — Inam land: gifted land; revenue went to a chosen beneficiary (e.g. a man of exceptional talent) to sustain himself.","difficulty":"easy","tags":["land-categories","jagir","khalisa","inam"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p9","origin":"FYQ_Pre_9","statement":"Match the Mughal revenue hierarchy roles to their administrative levels:\n1. Patwari — A. Pargana\n2. Qanungo — B. Sarkar (district)\n3. Amalguzar — C. Village","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1-A, 2-B, 3-C"},{"id":"b","text":"1-C, 2-A, 3-B"},{"id":"c","text":"1-B, 2-C, 3-A"},{"id":"d","text":"1-A, 2-C, 3-B"}],"answer":"b","explanation":"'Who collected revenue':\nPatwari — Village level (maintained ledgers of individual peasant holdings and crops).\nQanungo — Pargana level (consolidated Patwari data; hereditary custodian of historical tax rates).\nAmalguzar — Sarkar (district) level (Amil at pargana level reported to Amalguzar at sarkar level).","difficulty":"medium","tags":["revenue-hierarchy","patwari","qanungo","amalguzar"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p10","origin":"FYQ_Pre_10","statement":"With reference to ryot categories under Mughal Land Revenue, consider the following statements:\n1. Khudkashts cultivated the same land year after year and acquired customary occupancy rights.\n2. Pahikashts cultivated different lands across different seasons and had no occupancy rights.\n3. Pahikashts were sometimes called Vagrant or Banjara peasants.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"'Who were the ryots':\nStatement 1 ✓ — Khudkashts cultivated the same land year after year and acquired customary occupancy rights, documented in a Patta.\nStatement 2 ✓ — Pahikashts cultivated different lands across different seasons, often as share-croppers, with no occupancy rights and no legal protections.\nStatement 3 ✓ — Pahikashts were sometimes called Vagrant or Banjara peasants because of this rootlessness.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["ryots","khudkasht","pahikasht"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p11","origin":"FYQ_Pre_11","statement":"Under Akbar's Zabti system, the Zamindar's legally fixed commission for collecting LR was approximately:","options":[{"id":"a","text":"5% (called Peshkash)"},{"id":"b","text":"10% (called Nankar or Malikana)"},{"id":"c","text":"15% (called Abwabs)"},{"id":"d","text":"20% (called Milkiyat)"}],"answer":"b","explanation":"✓ — 'Who collected revenue': Under Akbar's Zabti system, the Zamindar's legally fixed commission was around 10%, called Nankar or Malikana.\n(a) ✗ — Peshkash was the 10% tribute the Watan Jagir holder paid the King, not the Zamindar's commission.\n(c) ✗ — Abwabs were customary additional tributes, not the commission.\n(d) ✗ — Milkiyat was the Zamindar's own personal lands.","difficulty":"hard","tags":["zabti","zamindar","nankar-malikana"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p12","origin":"FYQ_Pre_12","statement":"Which one of the following best describes the Ijaradari System?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Direct state collection of revenue through scientifically measured demand under Akbar's centralised administration."},{"id":"b","text":"Auctioning the right to collect taxes to a private bidder (an Ijaradar or Revenue Farmer) for a 3- to 5-year contract."},{"id":"c","text":"Hereditary Zamindari grants given to Rajput chieftains in exchange for military service."},{"id":"d","text":"Cash payments to Mansabdars in lieu of Jagir grants."}],"answer":"b","explanation":"'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system': The right to collect all revenues from an area — land, traders, shopkeepers — was auctioned to the highest bidder, called an Ijaradar or Revenue Farmer; contracts were typically 3 to 5 years.\n(a) ✗ — That describes the Zabti system, not Ijaradari.\n(c) ✗ — describes Watan Jagir grants.\n(d) ✗ — describes Naqdi Mansabdar payment.","difficulty":"medium","tags":["ijaradari","revenue-farming"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p13","origin":"FYQ_Pre_13","statement":"Arrange the following Mughal-era Ijaradari milestones in correct chronological order:\n1. Akbar abolished revenue farming and replaced it with the Zabti system.\n2. Jahandar Shah (r. 1712–13) institutionalised Ijaradari in Punjab and Bengal.\n3. Farukhsiyar (r. 1713–19) extended Ijaradari into royal Khalisa lands.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 — 2 — 3"},{"id":"b","text":"2 — 1 — 3"},{"id":"c","text":"1 — 3 — 2"},{"id":"d","text":"3 — 2 — 1"}],"answer":"a","explanation":"'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system':\n1. Akbar (1556–1605) practically abolished Ijaradari and replaced it with the Zabti system.\n2. Jahandar Shah (1712–13) institutionalised Ijaradari in the richest provinces — Punjab and Bengal.\n3. Farukhsiyar (1713–19) extended Ijaradari fatally into royal Khalisa lands.","difficulty":"easy","tags":["ijaradari","chronology"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p14","origin":"FYQ_Pre_14","statement":"With reference to Akbar's religious vision, consider the following statements:\n1. Ibadat Khana (1575) was established at Fatehpur Sikri for inter-faith debates.\n2. The Mahzar (1579) made the Emperor, not the clergy, the final authority on religious disputes.\n3. The Din-i-Ilahi (1582) drew on Islam, Hinduism, Zoroastrianism, and Christianity but attracted very few formal followers.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"1 and 2 only"},{"id":"b","text":"2 and 3 only"},{"id":"c","text":"1 and 3 only"},{"id":"d","text":"1, 2 and 3"}],"answer":"d","explanation":"'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?':\nStatement 1 ✓ — 'Ibadat Khana (1575)': Ibadat Khana 1575, House of Worship at Fatehpur Sikri.\nStatement 2 ✓ — 'Mahzar': Mahzar 1579, Emperor (not the clergy) became final word on matters of faith.\nStatement 3 ✓ — 'Din-i-Ilahi (1582)': Din-i-Ilahi 1582, syncretic order borrowing from Islam, Hinduism, Zoroastrianism, & Christianity; very few formal followers.","difficulty":"easy","tags":["akbar","religious-vision","din-i-ilahi"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-p15","origin":"FYQ_Pre_15","statement":"Which one of the following statements about the introduction of Jizya in India is correct?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Muhammad bin Qasim first imposed Jizya in Sindh during the 8th-century Arab conquest."},{"id":"b","text":"Qutb-ud-din Aibak first introduced Jizya in India in the early 13th century."},{"id":"c","text":"Akbar was the first ruler to abolish Jizya across the Mughal Empire."},{"id":"d","text":"Aurangzeb was the first ruler to impose Jizya across the Indian subcontinent."}],"answer":"a","explanation":"'Who actually introduced Jizya in India?': Muhammad bin Qasim first imposed Jizya in Sindh during the Arab conquest of the 8th century.\n(b) ✗ — Qutb-ud-din Aibak and his successors institutionalised Jizya as a formal instrument across the Delhi Sultanate from the early 13th century, but did not first introduce it.\n(c) ✗ — Akbar abolished Jizya, but he was not the first ruler to do so (intermediate rulers had varied policies).\n(d) ✗ — Aurangzeb reimposed Jizya, but it had existed in India for centuries before him.","difficulty":"hard","tags":["jizya","taxation"]}],"mains":[{"id":"hist-mg-c1-m1","origin":"PYQ_M.1","question":"\"Examine the main aspects of Akbar's religious syncretism.\"","keyPoints":["Ibadat Khana (1575) — House of Worship at Fatehpur Sikri; multi-faith debates; exposed Akbar to diversity of religious thought and to bitter Ulama rivalries (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?').","Mahzar (1579) — Infallibility Decree — gave Akbar authority to adjudicate religious disputes; effectively made the Emperor, not the clergy, the final word on matters of faith (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?').","Din-i-Ilahi (1582) — syncretic spiritual order borrowing from Islam, Hinduism, Zoroastrianism, & Christianity; very few formal followers; significance lay in the principle expressed (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?').","Sulh-i-Kul — universal peace — State must treat all religions with equal respect; no single faith should dominate policy. Became the ideological foundation of Mughal governance under Akbar and continued to influence Mughal politics long after his death (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?')."],"modelAnswer":"Closing line: the four-part sequence (Ibadat Khana → Mahzar → Din-i-Ilahi → Sulh-i-Kul) shows Akbar moving deliberately from open inter-faith debate, to State authority over religion, to a syncretic spiritual formulation, to a governing principle that outlasted his reign.","explanation":"PYQ_M.1 — Mains 2025 — Mughal Religious Vision (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?'). No other PYQs from the verified 1996–2025 bank anchor solely to Ch 1.","wordLimit":150,"marks":10,"difficulty":"medium","tags":["akbar","religious-syncretism","sulh-i-kul"],"year":2025},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-m2","origin":"FYQ_M.1","question":"Examine the institutional foundations laid by Babur and Akbar for the Mughal Empire's longevity.","keyPoints":["Babur's establishment of the dynasty (1526) — Panipat I victory, geographic anchor in the Delhi heartland, integration of Central Asian (Timurid) and Indian governance traditions (see 'Mughal Take Over from Lodis').","Akbar's land revenue revolution — the Zabti system based on scientifically measured demand + a salaried bureaucracy under the Mansabdari system replaced the older revenue-farming model (see 'How did Akbar56-05 build the Mughal State — the Mansabdari System' and 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Akbar's religious-administrative synthesis — Sulh-i-Kul as State doctrine; Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, and Din-i-Ilahi as institutional expressions; Watan Jagirs for Rajput integration (see 'How did Akbar56-05 build the Mughal State — the Mansabdari System' and 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?').","Persianate court culture under Humayun's Safavid alliance — Persian language, art, and administrative grammar became the imperial standard (see 'Humayun30-40 & Sher Shah Suri40-45 (1540-45)').","Conclusion: the founding generations built four institutional pillars — political (dynasty), economic (Zabti), military-administrative (Mansabdari), and ideological (Sulh-i-Kul) — that together explain why the Mughal Empire could absorb pressures for nearly two centuries (see 'What was Akbar56-05's religious vision — Sulh-i-Kul, Ibadat Khana, Mahzar, Din-i-Ilahi?')."],"modelAnswer":"Conclusion: the founding generations built four institutional pillars — political (dynasty), economic (Zabti), military-administrative (Mansabdari), and ideological (Sulh-i-Kul) — that together explain why the Mughal Empire could absorb pressures for nearly two centuries.","explanation":"Demand: Identify the founding-era institutions and weigh how each contributed to the Mughal Empire's later longevity.","wordLimit":250,"marks":15,"difficulty":"medium","tags":["babur","akbar","institutions","mansabdari","zabti"]},{"id":"hist-mg-c1-m3","origin":"FYQ_M.2","question":"Discuss the evolution of the Mughal land revenue system from Akbar's Zabti to the late-Mughal Ijaradari, and its consequences for the State and the peasantry.","keyPoints":["Akbar's Zabti (1556-1605) — scientifically measured demand based on area + average yield + standard prices, with the Patwari-Qanungo-Amalguzar hierarchy reporting on actual cultivation. State capacity high; peasant burden predictable (see 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Continuation under Akbar's successors — Jahangir, Shah Jahan, and early Aurangzeb retained the framework, with limited shifts to Ijaradari at the margins (see 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Jahandar Shah (1712-13) — first institutionalisation of Ijaradari in the richest provinces (Punjab + Bengal); private bidders bought 3-5 year revenue rights at auction (see 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Farukhsiyar (1713-19) — fatal extension of Ijaradari into royal Khalisa lands; the State's own income now came through middlemen with extractive incentives (see 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Consequence for the State — short-term cash inflow but loss of administrative knowledge about real revenue capacity; the State's grip on revenue weakened over decades.","Consequence for the peasantry — Ijaradars had 3-5 year horizons, no incentive for long-term investment; over-extraction, peasant flight, and the rise of revenue arrears characterise the later-Mughal countryside (see 'Mughal Land Revenue (LR) system').","Conclusion: the Zabti-to-Ijaradari trajectory mirrors the wider Mughal decline — institutional rigour gave way to short-term cash, with State capacity and peasant welfare both eroding in parallel."],"modelAnswer":"Conclusion: the Zabti-to-Ijaradari trajectory mirrors the wider Mughal decline — institutional rigour gave way to short-term cash, with State capacity and peasant welfare both eroding in parallel.","explanation":"Demand: Trace the change from Akbar's scientifically measured Zabti to the auction-based Ijaradari, and assess what each meant for State capacity and peasant welfare.","wordLimit":250,"marks":15,"difficulty":"medium","tags":["zabti","ijaradari","land-revenue","mughal-decline"]}]}$chapter$::jsonb, 'published', now(), now()
